- Did I know that?

231
00:10:25,961 --> 00:10:29,588
Um, I don't know. Did you?

232
00:10:29,589 --> 00:10:32,842
I don't think I did.
No, I definitely didn't.

233
00:10:34,970 --> 00:10:36,011
Why didn't you tell me?

234
00:10:36,012 --> 00:10:38,055
Uh, I don't know,
it didn't seem that important.

235
00:10:38,056 --> 00:10:39,432
Lots of people make partner.

236
00:10:41,142 --> 00:10:42,519
I guess it just slipped my mind.

237
00:10:43,270 --> 00:10:45,146
[scoffs] It slipped your mind?

238
00:10:46,773 --> 00:10:47,815
What do you want me to say?

239
00:10:47,816 --> 00:10:50,067
She works hard,
she's been at the firm for a long time.

240
00:10:50,068 --> 00:10:53,112
When you do those things,
at a certain point you make partner.

241
00:10:53,113 --> 00:10:54,363
Yeah, but Vanessa is different.

242
00:10:54,364 --> 00:10:56,740
We went to law school together,
we clerked together.

243
00:10:56,741 --> 00:10:58,325
And you know how I feel about her.

244
00:10:58,326 --> 00:11:01,454
It's like she represents
everything that I could have been.

245
00:11:02,038 --> 00:11:04,499
Babe, I... I hear you. I-I really do.

246
00:11:05,542 --> 00:11:07,460
But she's not living some magical life.

247
00:11:08,295 --> 00:11:10,170
You know, she probably envies you.

248
00:11:10,171 --> 00:11:12,841
She's probably saying things
to her husband about you.

249
00:11:13,341 --> 00:11:14,241
Like what?

250
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:19,805
I... I d... I don't know.
I'm not in their conversations.

251
00:11:19,806 --> 00:11:22,558
Maybe about you buying the house,
fixing it up,

252
00:11:22,559 --> 00:11:24,268
and being, you know, like, creative.

253
00:11:24,269 --> 00:11:25,644
You don't believe that.

254
00:11:25,645 --> 00:11:29,148
It sounds like a lot more fun than arguing
about a legal contract for five hours

255
00:11:29,149 --> 00:11:31,150
around a conference table
where you can't cross your legs

256
00:11:31,151 --> 00:11:32,986
because there are so many AV wires.

257
00:11:34,738 --> 00:11:38,157
Uh, you know what? I'm sorry, babe.
I... It's not a big deal, right.

258
00:11:38,158 --> 00:11:41,535
This weekend is about you,
and I'm... I'm so proud of you.

259
00:11:41,536 --> 00:11:45,332
I just want you to enjoy yourself
and en-enjoy the AV wires.

260
00:11:45,874 --> 00:11:47,334
[chuckles] Thank you.

261
00:11:48,668 --> 00:11:52,838
And you enjoy your afternoon.
And I'll see you at the reception tonight.

262
00:11:52,839 --> 00:11:54,674
- Okay. Love you.
- Love you.

263
00:11:56,259 --> 00:11:58,969
[Tasmin] Did you hear Milton
got taken off of Dupont?

264
00:11:58,970 --> 00:12:00,304
[lawyer] Wait, what?

265
00:12:00,305 --> 00:12:03,724
- I thought the Suarez case was his thing.
- Used to be.

266
00:12:03,725 --> 00:12:06,268
- Wow.
- Oh, Paul with the printer.

267
00:12:06,269 --> 00:12:07,770
- [Paul] Hey, hey.
- Yes! [laughs]

268
00:12:07,771 --> 00:12:10,856
They told me there were plugs up here
so I figured I'd... I'd bring it up.

269
00:12:10,857 --> 00:12:11,982
Yeah, might as well.

270
00:12:11,983 --> 00:12:14,318
Whoo-hoo! Problem solved!

271
00:12:14,319 --> 00:12:15,736
[Tasmin] Did you bring a laptop cord?

272
00:12:15,737 --> 00:12:17,905
[Paul] Uh, no. Where are my nachos?
I ordered nachos.

273
00:12:17,906 --> 00:12:19,907
- [Tasmin] How'd you order 'em?
- [Paul] Fully loaded.

274
00:12:19,908 --> 00:12:21,159
[Tasmin] That's what I thought.

275
00:12:29,501 --> 00:12:31,461
Oh, sorry.

276
00:12:32,712 --> 00:12:33,713
Uh, sorry. [sighs]

277
00:12:36,216 --> 00:12:37,300
<i>All rise.</i>

278
00:12:38,718 --> 00:12:40,478
[Judge]
<i>Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen.</i>

279
00:12:41,096 --> 00:12:44,306
[announcer 1] <i>This court now sentences you
to two and a half years in the Clark...</i>

280
00:12:44,307 --> 00:12:47,893
[announcer 2] <i>Next on Courtroom Live,
a mother of three sues her alma mater</i>

281
00:12:47,894 --> 00:12:49,979
<i>when career opportunities th...</i>

282
00:12:49,980 --> 00:12:51,063
[sighs]

283
00:12:51,064 --> 00:12:54,733
[Milton, muffled] You can't just take me
off Dupont, I brought that case in.

284
00:12:54,734 --> 00:12:58,363
I'm not just some associate,
I'm a partner. I'm a partner!

285
00:12:59,072 --> 00:13:00,115
[sighs]

286
00:13:11,543 --> 00:13:14,503
I don't see what the problem is.
My kids and I love Johnny 66.

287
00:13:14,504 --> 00:13:16,297
That does not make me feel better at all.

288
00:13:16,298 --> 00:13:17,965
Well,
it's not meant to make you feel better.

289
00:13:17,966 --> 00:13:20,175
- It's meant to make our kids feel better.
- Why did we meet here?

290
00:13:20,176 --> 00:13:21,635
This is the lamest part of downtown.

291
00:13:21,636 --> 00:13:25,347
You know, I was just really hungry.
And I also have this desire

292
00:13:25,348 --> 00:13:28,642
to be surrounded by classic cars
and old American nostalgia

293
00:13:28,643 --> 00:13:30,477
from when this country was a better place.

294
00:13:30,478 --> 00:13:33,607
I found a way to reconcile
those two desires. Look.

295
00:13:34,357 --> 00:13:37,443
Oh no, not here.
No, no, no, no, I'm not going.

296
00:13:37,444 --> 00:13:39,653
No, there's so many better places
to eat around here.

297
00:13:39,654 --> 00:13:42,573
- Don't be a square. Come on. Come on.
- Oh, come on, don't do that.

298
00:13:42,574 --> 00:13:44,826
I can't be seen
going into a place like this.

299
00:13:45,410 --> 00:13:47,912
- [Sylvia] Mmm?
- [Will] Mmm.

300
00:13:47,913 --> 00:13:49,413
- Hello.
- Hi.

301
00:13:49,414 --> 00:13:51,415
[chuckles] Uh, table for two, please.

302
00:13:51,416 --> 00:13:55,127
Oh, well, your pit crew will have your
table ready in one minute and counting.

303
00:13:55,128 --> 00:13:57,214
- [chuckles] Huh? [laughing]
- All right, thank you.

304
00:13:58,673 --> 00:14:01,634
The fact that you like this place
is the most unknowable thing about you.

305
00:14:01,635 --> 00:14:03,052
Oh, I love this place.

306
00:14:03,053 --> 00:14:05,429
Now, why do we have Rosa Parks on the wall

307
00:14:05,430 --> 00:14:09,725
next to three girls drinking milkshakes,
above a car Adolf Hitler designed?

308
00:14:09,726 --> 00:14:11,770
It's your country. You explain it.

309
00:14:12,437 --> 00:14:14,313
Least she's at the front
of the restaurant.

310
00:14:14,314 --> 00:14:16,398
[chuckles] Who's this fucking guy?

311
00:14:16,399 --> 00:14:18,525
Oh, you know who that is?

312
00:14:18,526 --> 00:14:21,612
That's the founder and visionary
of Johnny 66.

313
00:14:21,613 --> 00:14:23,697
- It's Johnny Rev.
- That's not a real name.

314
00:14:23,698 --> 00:14:25,741
If it was, that would be truly miraculous.

315
00:14:25,742 --> 00:14:27,952
He is actually a very interesting guy.

316
00:14:27,953 --> 00:14:30,205
He's very smart.
I heard him interviewed on NPR.

317
00:14:30,789 --> 00:14:33,166
They consider him a disrupter.

318
00:14:33,708 --> 00:14:37,002
Look he's, uh, disrupting people's
buttholes after they eat his onion rings.

319
00:14:37,003 --> 00:14:38,712
[Sylvia] Listen, you could learn from him.

320
00:14:38,713 --> 00:14:41,507
[Will] What? How to become a hybrid
of a human and a tanning bed?

321
00:14:41,508 --> 00:14:44,635
How to run a beloved
and successful business.

322
00:14:44,636 --> 00:14:49,098
Honestly, this place fucking sucks,
and I want nothing to do with it. [gasps]

323
00:14:49,099 --> 00:14:50,433
That was cool.

324
00:14:51,768 --> 00:14:54,395
- Follow me.
- Thank you, I love your hair.

325
00:14:54,396 --> 00:14:57,190
- [chuckles] Oh, they make me do this.
- That's great.

326
00:14:57,691 --> 00:14:59,776
[gasps] Merch.

327
00:15:00,360 --> 00:15:01,902
[Will] Do people actually buy this shit?

328
00:15:01,903 --> 00:15:03,321
Ah, just have a little look.

329
00:15:05,574 --> 00:15:08,242
[sighs] How many doo-wop songs are there?

330
00:15:08,243 --> 00:15:09,994
You know,
if you listen to the words carefully,

331
00:15:09,995 --> 00:15:13,038
every single one of them
is about having sex with an underage girl.

332
00:15:13,039 --> 00:15:14,540
It's a disgusting genre.

333
00:15:14,541 --> 00:15:16,917
I'm so bummed they didn't have
the mozzarella stick shifts.

334
00:15:16,918 --> 00:15:18,502
They're so good. You would've loved them.

335
00:15:18,503 --> 00:15:20,087
The beer... The beer is garbage.

336
00:15:20,088 --> 00:15:23,090
You should try a fender blender.
They're very strong.

337
00:15:23,091 --> 00:15:24,174
What's in there?

338
00:15:24,175 --> 00:15:26,176
Everything that's in a piña colada.

339
00:15:26,177 --> 00:15:29,555
- So it's a piña colada?
- No, it's a fender blender.

340
00:15:29,556 --> 00:15:31,181
- That's good branding.
- You want to get one?

341
00:15:31,182 --> 00:15:33,434
- I'm okay, I'm... Thank you.
- Come on.

342
00:15:33,435 --> 00:15:34,727
[car horn beeps]

343
00:15:34,728 --> 00:15:37,021
<i>♪ Happy birthday
Happy, happy, birthday ♪</i>

344
00:15:37,022 --> 00:15:40,190
<i>♪ Happy birthday
Happy, happy birthday ♪</i>

345
00:15:40,191 --> 00:15:45,738
<i>♪ Happy birthday
Happy, happy, birthday ♪</i>

346
00:15:45,739 --> 00:15:49,658
<i>♪ Happy birthday
Happy, happy, birthday to you ♪</i>

347
00:15:49,659 --> 00:15:52,912
- Vroom, vroom. Happy birthday, Daddy-o.
- Thank you.

348
00:15:52,913 --> 00:15:55,205
Love you, baby doll!

349
00:15:55,206 --> 00:15:57,374
- Not my birthday.
- Thanks, guys. He's lying.

350
00:15:57,375 --> 00:15:58,834
- You proud of yourself?
- Happy birthday.

351
00:15:58,835 --> 00:16:01,880
You know my wish? That a meteorite
kills us all, right now.

352
00:16:02,923 --> 00:16:04,299
[laughing]

353
00:16:05,842 --> 00:16:09,930
I'll give it to Johnny Rev, which I assume
is short for "Johnathan Revolution."

354
00:16:10,889 --> 00:16:13,432
These are delicious, and these booths
are very fun to sit in.

355
00:16:13,433 --> 00:16:15,309
- See?
- And the food is pretty fucking good.

356
00:16:15,310 --> 00:16:18,771
- Mmm, somebody changing their mind?
- No, not at all.

357
00:16:18,772 --> 00:16:20,148
I-I'm confused.

358
00:16:20,649 --> 00:16:24,360
Isn't the point of starting a brewery
just to sell a lot of beer?

359
00:16:24,361 --> 00:16:26,904
The point is to sell good beer,
which we are doing.

360
00:16:26,905 --> 00:16:28,739
And I'm very happy
with our level of success,

361
00:16:28,740 --> 00:16:30,241
and I have no interest in selling out to,

362
00:16:30,242 --> 00:16:32,076
like, a giant corporate conglomerate.

363
00:16:32,077 --> 00:16:33,827
That's a little bit illogical. Come on.

364
00:16:33,828 --> 00:16:36,538
Like, you're just gonna be
making beer and selling beer

365
00:16:36,539 --> 00:16:38,082
and probably make a lot of money.

366
00:16:38,083 --> 00:16:39,959
- And...
- Why is everyone so obsessed with money?

367
00:16:39,960 --> 00:16:45,673
Whoa. Take it easy.
Back up, Alexandria Cortazio-Cortez.

368
00:16:45,674 --> 00:16:47,007
Not even almost her name.

369
00:16:47,008 --> 00:16:49,528
I don't think you got...
I think you got one out of three right.

370
00:16:50,428 --> 00:16:52,430
Okay. Wha... What's really going on?

371
00:16:56,768 --> 00:16:58,353
- I'm gonna be honest with you.
- Mmm.

372
00:17:00,355 --> 00:17:02,524
- I am cool.
- Mmm.

373
00:17:03,400 --> 00:17:04,900
I'm... I'm a cool.

374
00:17:04,901 --> 00:17:06,443
- I'm in the cool category.
- "A cool"?

375
00:17:06,444 --> 00:17:08,153
- I'm a cool guy.
- Singular?

376
00:17:08,154 --> 00:17:11,908
This place? Not fucking cool. It's uncool.

377
00:17:12,700 --> 00:17:16,286
And if you're like me, that is terrifying.
Okay?

378
00:17:16,287 --> 00:17:18,414
- You gotta stay cool. Gotta stay cool.
- I gotta stay cool.

379
00:17:18,415 --> 00:17:19,747
I can't not be cool.

380
00:17:19,748 --> 00:17:22,251
Nobody is saying that you're not cool.

381
00:17:22,252 --> 00:17:24,294
This place would be saying I'm not cool.

382
00:17:24,295 --> 00:17:26,547
Nobody's saying you're not cool.

383
00:17:26,548 --> 00:17:31,302
I'm just suggesting that maybe
at this point in our lives

384
00:17:31,303 --> 00:17:34,889
when we're at this age, that maybe
we should focus less on being cool

385
00:17:34,890 --> 00:17:37,391
and more on acting our age.

386
00:17:37,392 --> 00:17:41,353
Well, that was spoken
like a true lamazoid.

387
00:17:41,354 --> 00:17:43,522
I just can't be a corporate sellout.

388
00:17:43,523 --> 00:17:45,649
Well, you gotta go tell Andy.

389
00:17:45,650 --> 00:17:47,651
He went to business school.
I don't know what to say.

390
00:17:47,652 --> 00:17:50,362
I'm a lawyer. I'll come with you.
We'll sort it out.

391
00:17:50,363 --> 00:17:52,198
- I'll come with you.
- Oh, thank you.

392
00:17:55,243 --> 00:17:58,120
[snickers] You guys look fucking insane.

393
00:17:58,121 --> 00:18:01,081
Yeah, and I'll tell you why.
We were at Johnny 66.

394
00:18:01,082 --> 00:18:02,625
We had a great time.

395
00:18:02,626 --> 00:18:04,585
The cake was good,
and it came in a little car,

396
00:18:04,586 --> 00:18:06,337
but other than that
it fucking sucks there,

397
00:18:06,338 --> 00:18:08,631
and we cannot have this guy
coming here tonight,

398
00:18:08,632 --> 00:18:11,842
trying all of our delicious beers
and making us an offer we can't refuse.

399
00:18:11,843 --> 00:18:14,178
I think we should serve our beers
at Johnny 66.

400
00:18:14,179 --> 00:18:16,765
Yeah, I want to completely sell out
and make money.

401
00:18:17,349 --> 00:18:20,559
Are you kidding me, man?
Have you been inside of a Johnny 66?

402
00:18:20,560 --> 00:18:22,561
I have. It's not good.

403
00:18:22,562 --> 00:18:24,855
There was a painting on the wall
of Martin Luther King

404
00:18:24,856 --> 00:18:26,524
on a surfboard with Fred Flintstone,

405
00:18:27,108 --> 00:18:29,735
and even in the painting
Martin Luther King was like, "Really?"

406
00:18:29,736 --> 00:18:33,864
Whatever. Whatever. I googled them,
and there's a fuck ton of them.

407
00:18:33,865 --> 00:18:35,241
Meaning we can make a lot of money.

408
00:18:35,242 --> 00:18:39,870
You know, what makes me sad at night
is how obsessed with "money" everyone is.

409
00:18:39,871 --> 00:18:41,413
Well, we live in America.

410
00:18:41,414 --> 00:18:44,708
- Right. It's a capitalist society.
- With money, you can buy a car.

411
00:18:44,709 --> 00:18:46,377
Or it gets you a printer for your house,

412
00:18:46,378 --> 00:18:48,546
so you can get me that fucking W-4
I've been asking for.

413
00:18:48,547 --> 00:18:51,131
- I know the things money does.
- You know what I think?

414
00:18:51,132 --> 00:18:53,425
You don't want this deal
to work out because it came from Reggie,

415
00:18:53,426 --> 00:18:55,803
and you fucking hate Reggie
because he's Audrey's brother.

416
00:18:55,804 --> 00:18:58,013
And you're clearly not over
your goddamn divorce

417
00:18:58,014 --> 00:19:00,641
so you're gonna tank every idea he has,
even if it's a fucking good one.

418
00:19:00,642 --> 00:19:02,851
That's actually very insightful.

419
00:19:02,852 --> 00:19:05,688
- This is about the divorce, and...
- Don't start fucking therapizing me.

420
00:19:05,689 --> 00:19:09,108
- Go... Go open a practice together.
- Fuck, maybe we should. Maybe we should.

421
00:19:09,109 --> 00:19:12,111
I bet you I'd make more money there
than I do in this fucking place.

422
00:19:12,112 --> 00:19:15,781
Look, I'm just saying it wouldn't kill us
to get a little more liquid. That's all.

423
00:19:15,782 --> 00:19:19,327
All I know is that this place
is always full, and we're both doing fine.

424
00:19:19,828 --> 00:19:23,706
[sighs] Fuck fine. I want more than fine.
Goddamn it. You know this.

425
00:19:23,707 --> 00:19:27,418
I wanna be married, bro.
I wanna start a family, do family shit.

426
00:19:27,419 --> 00:19:30,212
You just think you want that. You don't
actually fucking want that. You're fine.

427
00:19:30,213 --> 00:19:31,882
- Where are you going?
- Nowhere.

428
00:19:37,971 --> 00:19:39,139
- [Sylvia] Will?
- Yeah.

429
00:19:40,223 --> 00:19:41,640
You're spilling the beer.

430
00:19:41,641 --> 00:19:44,435
I know I am. Can't serve beer
if there is no beer.

431
00:19:44,436 --> 00:19:45,853
Hey, what are you doing?

432
00:19:45,854 --> 00:19:48,397
Hey, Omar. Will you help me,
uh, empty this tank over here?

433
00:19:48,398 --> 00:19:49,482
- Oh, yeah.
- Thank you.

434
00:19:50,525 --> 00:19:53,277
The-These tanks look like
they hold a-a lot of beer.

435
00:19:53,278 --> 00:19:54,194
They do.

436
00:19:54,195 --> 00:19:56,739
And that's a very small hose,
and there's a lot of tanks in here.

437
00:19:56,740 --> 00:19:58,741
But it is a largely symbolic gesture.

438
00:19:58,742 --> 00:20:01,368
Well, and there's also some
cans of beer behind you.

439
00:20:01,369 --> 00:20:04,079
Those are cider, not beer.
But I can empty those too.

440
00:20:04,080 --> 00:20:06,206
Yeah. You'd like the cider.
Ladies love cider.

441
00:20:06,207 --> 00:20:07,708
- [Andy] Dude, Will.
- I do like cider.

442
00:20:07,709 --> 00:20:09,668
- I'm Sylvia.
- Will, what the fuck are you doing, bro?

443
00:20:09,669 --> 00:20:12,379
- [Will] Hey.
- Goddamn it! What the... Stop it.

444
00:20:12,380 --> 00:20:13,422
Gimme the fucking... Don't...

445
00:20:13,423 --> 00:20:14,590
- Ah! Stop it!
- [Sylvia screams]

446
00:20:14,591 --> 00:20:17,092
- [Will] No! I won't stop. No!
- [Andy] Hey. Gimme the hose.

447
00:20:17,093 --> 00:20:18,886
- Get outta here.
- [Will] No! Fuck you.

448
00:20:18,887 --> 00:20:21,597
[grunts] It's in my eyes, you dick!
What are you doing?

449
00:20:21,598 --> 00:20:22,973
I will not go down without a fight!

450
00:20:22,974 --> 00:20:26,393
[pants] What you said
about Audrey is not true, okay?

451
00:20:26,394 --> 00:20:29,271
Yeah, I've moved on from that.
I've resolved that situation emotionally.

452
00:20:29,272 --> 00:20:31,523
I even got my stuff out
of her place, okay?

453
00:20:31,524 --> 00:20:33,651
This has to do with the fact that
I hate Reggie,

454
00:20:33,652 --> 00:20:37,029
and I do not hate him because
he is Audrey's stepbrother!

455
00:20:37,030 --> 00:20:39,490
I hate him because he's
